<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12069e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12069e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12069e"> 69(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Cyrographum / Litis Divisio / souch cheque / v false abbatial titledeed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il suffit de remarquer que la charte confirmant la pr&eacute;tendue donation est dat&eacute;e de 1085; or, elle est sign&eacute;e de L&eacute;ofric, lequel mourut en 1072. Elle porte donc en elle-m&ecirc;me la preuve de sa fausset&eacute;. Ces supercheries ne sont pas rares; tant&ocirc;t elles proc&egrave;dent d&apos;un exc&egrave;s d&apos;amour des religieux pour leur moustier; plus l&apos;origine de l&apos;abbaye ou du prieur&eacute; &eacute;tait recul&eacute;e, plus grande paraissait sa gloire; tant&ocirc;t les faussaires avaient pour but de faciliter aux descendants des donateurs la revendication des biens conc&eacute;d&eacute;s par leurs anc&ecirc;tres. Cette pratique coupable, contre laquelle des peines s&eacute;v&egrave;res &eacute;taient &eacute;dict&eacute;es, fit na&icirc;tre les chartes doubles, sur lesquelles on &eacute;crivait en grosses lettres les mots CYROGRAPHUM ou LITIS DIVISIO; on coupait ensuite le titre en deux parties, soit en ligne droite, soit <font color="green">[262]</font> en ligne ondul&eacute;e, soit en dents de scies ou en cr&eacute;neaux, mais ces endentures ne supprim&egrave;rent pas les fraudes. <br><font color="green">[It is enough to say that the charter that seems to confirm this donation is dated 1085; yet it is signed by Leofric, who died in 1072. It carries thus in itself the proof its mendacity. These frauds are not rare; mostly they derive from an excessive love on the part of the monks for their monastery; the older the abbey or the priory, the greater its glory; so the forgers wanted to help the descendants of the donors to regain the goods that had been given by their ancestors. This guilty practice, against which severe penalties were enacted, gave rise to double charters, on which one wrote in large letters the words <mark>CYROGRAPHUM or LITIS DIVISIO; the title was then cut in two, either in a straight or a wavy line or in saw teeth or in battlements, but these indentures did not suppress the frauds</mark>.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 262-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
